    vellum_post_368 = Post()
    vellum_post_368.title = u'Lemon Balm Tincture'
    vellum_post_368.slug = u'lemon-balm-tincture'
    vellum_post_368.author = None
    vellum_post_368.markup = u'markdown'
    vellum_post_368.body = u'I\'ve an abundance of dried <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemon_balm" >Lemon Balm</a> hanging around, so last night I decided to tincture 2/3 of it. Trouble is, none of my books contained alcohol percentages or ratios for the herb. Google seemed to think that 100 proof alcohol would be fine, but couldn\'t come to a conclusion as to the ratio. Some sites said 1:1, some 1:4, and still others claimed 1:5.\n\nThe most important part of tincturing, I\'ve been taught, is that the herb is completely covered for the first two weeks. I made my measurements to use the 1:5 ratio, but, to cover everything, ended up with a mixture closer to 1:16. Let\'s hope it turns out.\n\nIn one and a half moon cycles, it will be ready for use -- calming nervous systems, fighting fever, helping digestion, and even combating herpes (hey, you never know).'
    vellum_post_368.body_rendered = u'<p>I&#8217;ve an abundance of dried <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemon_balm">Lemon Balm</a> hanging around, so last night I decided to tincture 2/3 of it. Trouble is, none of my books contained alcohol percentages or ratios for the herb. Google seemed to think that 100 proof alcohol would be fine, but couldn&#8217;t come to a conclusion as to the ratio. Some sites said 1:1, some 1:4, and still others claimed 1:5.</p>\n<p>The most important part of tincturing, I&#8217;ve been taught, is that the herb is completely covered for the first two weeks. I made my measurements to use the 1:5 ratio, but, to cover everything, ended up with a mixture closer to 1:16. Let&#8217;s hope it turns out.</p>\n<p>In one and a half moon cycles, it will be ready for use &#8212; calming nervous systems, fighting fever, helping digestion, and even combating herpes (hey, you never know).</p>'
