    vellum_post_669 = Post()
    vellum_post_669.title = u'Signal to Noise'
    vellum_post_669.slug = u'signal-to-noise'
    vellum_post_669.author = None
    vellum_post_669.markup = u'markdown'
    vellum_post_669.body = u'Today I finished reading Eric S. Nylund\'s <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0380792923/qid=1110655010/sr=8-1/ref=sr_8_xs_ap_i1_xgl14/102-8126296-6853733?v=glance&s=books&n=507846" >Signal to Noise</a>. I\'ve had somewhat of a love-hate relationship with the book, but, in the end, love prevails and I\'d recommend it to any cyberpunk fan.\nAlthough it\'s not your average cyberpunk. I think of cyberpunk as generally being placed in a sci-fi setting, but not focusing much on the actual science fiction. And, of course, cyberpunk has your post-apocalyptic/dystopia themes, too. Signal to Noise is leaning more toward normal science fiction -- they have aliens! -- and ends with the apocalypse, instead of taking place in it.\nIt ends in a cliff-hanger, too. Bastard.\n\nAll in all, a good book. I think Eric Nylund spent a <i>tad</i> too long at Microsoft, though. The whole book revolves around corporations and business.'
    vellum_post_669.body_rendered = u'<p>Today I finished reading Eric S. Nylund&#8217;s <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0380792923/qid=1110655010/sr=8-1/ref=sr_8_xs_ap_i1_xgl14/102-8126296-6853733?v=glance&amp;s=books&amp;n=507846">Signal to Noise</a>. I&#8217;ve had somewhat of a love-hate relationship with the book, but, in the end, love prevails and I&#8217;d recommend it to any cyberpunk fan.\nAlthough it&#8217;s not your average cyberpunk. I think of cyberpunk as generally being placed in a sci-fi setting, but not focusing much on the actual science fiction. And, of course, cyberpunk has your post-apocalyptic/dystopia themes, too. Signal to Noise is leaning more toward normal science fiction &#8212; they have aliens! &#8212; and ends with the apocalypse, instead of taking place in it.\nIt ends in a cliff-hanger, too. Bastard.</p>\n<p>All in all, a good book. I think Eric Nylund spent a <i>tad</i> too long at Microsoft, though. The whole book revolves around corporations and business.</p>'
